  "opinion": "As a woman who grew up in a small Italian town and now works in retail in Naples, I've seen firsthand how stereotypes can shadow even the most capable individuals. Stereotype threat in STEM isn't just an academic concept—it's the quiet anxiety that makes someone doubt their abilities when they're in a field where they're often told they don't belong. I remember when my own children were school-aged, I'd hear them say things like, 'Girls aren't good at math,' and it made me wonder if that was true. As a retail worker with only upper secondary education, I've noticed how many people in my community feel the same way about STEM fields, especially women and people of color. But here's the thing: addressing stereotype threat isn't about changing the world overnight. It starts with small, everyday actions. For instance, when I talk to my customers about science or technology, I try to keep it simple and relatable, avoiding jargon that might make them feel out of place. I also encourage my children to explore STEM through hands-on projects like building models or gardening—things that show science in action without the pressure of exams. The key is to create spaces where everyone feels welcome and capable, not just the ones who fit the 'ideal' mold. From my experience, it's not about fixing people but about building bridges of understanding and respect. And as a Buddhist, I believe in the interconnectedness of all beings, so addressing stereotype threat is part of a larger effort to create a more harmonious society where everyone has the chance to shine.",
